nib.text:
Six people were displaced by a fire in a Northeast Minneapolis home Tuesday morning, firefighters said. 

At around 7:56 a.m., firefighters responded to a report of a residential fire on the 400 block of Lowry Avenue NE. 

Upon arrival, crews located heavy flames in the roofline of the one-and-a-half story home. 

All six residentstwo adults and four childrenwere able to safely evacuate.

Firefighters ventilated the roof as they sprayed water on the blaze. 

Citizen user video showed flames and smoke rising through a ventilated area. 

By 8:25 a.m., a second alarm had been called to request additional units and resources to the scene. 

Within 30 minutes, the bulk of the fire had been put out, MFD officials said in a [Twitter thread](https://twitter.com/MinneapolisFire/status/1475842405039579140?s=20). 

Crews remained on the scene to search for hot spots and put out any additional flames for over an hour.

No injuries were reported among firefighters, residents, or civilians. 

The home was declared uninhabitable, and the Red Cross was called to assist the displaced family. 

The cause of the fire is under investigation.
